did.physloc: Materials are stored offsite and advance notice is required for use. Please contact university-archives@nyu.edu at least two business days prior to your research visit to coordinate access.
did.abstract: The School of Education Collection of Dissertations and Theses dates from 1940 to 1995 and contains student dissertations and theses from four academic departments within the school. The thesis topics vary widely in subject and time period.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The files remain in their original order and are grouped into two series based on the academic department of the thesis or dissertation.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The School of Education Collection of Dissertations and Theses dates from 1950 to 1995 and contains dissertations and theses on a broad range of topics pertaining to art history, education, nursing, and health across diverse geographical and historical categories. Many of the theses and dissertations are bound, and some are in multiple volumes.

bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: The School of Pedagogy at New York University was founded in 1890 and renamed the School of Education in 1921. From 1974 to 1994, the school was known as the School of Education, Health, Nursing, and Arts Professions (SEHNAP) from 1974 to 1994. In 2007, the school was renamed the Steinhardt School of Culture, Education, and Human Development.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: Published citations should take the following form:
Identification of item, date (if known); School of Education Collection of Dissertations and Theses; RG 26.0; box number; folder number; New York University Archives, New York University.

custodhist.head: Custodial History
custodhist.p: The Art and Arts Professions dissertations were transferred to the New York University Archives by the Department of Art and Arts Professions in 1997. Details on regarding the transfer of materials in Series II and III are not available.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: The collection's call number was changed from RG 26.0 to RG 26.35 in June 2019.

bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: The Department of Art and Art Professions is part of the New York University School of Education, which is currently called the Steinhardt School of Culture, Education, and Human Development. At the beginning of the period represented by this series, the School of Education's Art courses were taught within Art Education, a program that focused on the training of teachers, supervisors, and directors of art education in elementary and secondary schools. By the 1990s, the renamed Department of Art and Art Professions had expanded to offer majors in Studio Art, Arts Education, Art Therapy, and Arts Administration, offering a PhD in Arts and Humanities or Art Education. In the 1940s, PhD candidates in the department of Art Education spent at least one year working on what was then referred to as a thesis. By the 1990s, students in Art and Arts Professions produced dissertations as part of their PhD requirements.
